    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Take the matrix for rotation by <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> radians
          in <m>\RR^2</m> and muliply it by itself to check that the
          result is the matrix for rotation by <m>\pi</m> radians.
          Multiply by the original matrix again and check that the
          result is now the matrix for rotation by
          <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The matrix for a quarter turn rotation is 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          To compose transformations we multiply matrices. To compose
          this transformation with itselt, we mutiply the matrix with
          itself. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) = 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          The result of the matrix multiplication is indeed the
          rotation matrix for rotation by <m>\pi</m> radians. To see
          what happens after a third rotation by a quarter turn, we
          multiply this matrix by the original quarter turn matrix. 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) = 
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 0
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          The result of the matrix multiplication is indeed the matrix
          of the rotation by <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m> radians. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="dihedral-groups">
    <title>Dihedral Groups</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Make a multiplication table for the dihedral group
          <m>D_5</m>. (Label the rotations <m>R_i</m>; the index
          <m>i</m> indicates how many fifth of a full turn for the
          rotation. Label the reflections <m>F_i</m>; the index
          indicates reflection over a line through the <m>i</m>
          vertex, counting counterclockwise.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There are many multiplication to calculate. I recommend
          calculating matrices by vertex operaions. If we number the
          vertices of the pentagon counterclockwise from 1 to 5, then
          <m>R_2</m> (rotation by <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> of a turn) can be
          represented by this movement of vertices.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 \amp \mapsto 3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              2 \amp \mapsto 4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3 \amp \mapsto 5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4 \amp \mapsto 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              5 \amp \mapsto 2
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Reflection <m>F_3</m> (reflection over the line through
          vertex 3 and the middle of the opposite edge)) can be
          represented by this action on the vertices.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 \amp \mapsto 5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              2 \amp \mapsto 4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3 \amp \mapsto 3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4 \amp \mapsto 2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              5 \amp \mapsto 1
            </mrow>
          </md>
          To calculate <m>R_2 \circ F_3</m>, we can use these vertex
          changes. In composition, we do the right transformation
          first. Therefore, starting at vertex 1, <m>F_3</m> send it
          to vertex 5, and then <m>R_2</m> sends vertex 5 to vertex 2.
          Therefore, the whole composition sends vertex 1 to vertex 2.
          We calculate the movement of the other four vertices
          similarly. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 \amp \mapsto 2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              2 \amp \mapsto 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3 \amp \mapsto 5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4 \amp \mapsto 4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              5 \amp \mapsto 3
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then we have to identify this transformation, since is still
          should be something in the group. It cannot be a rotation,
          since vertex 4 is fixed. The only rotation that fixes vertex
          4 is <m>F_4</m>. Therefore, we have <m>R_2 \circ F_3 =
          F_4</m>. Note that the multiplication is not commutative. If
          we did <m>F_3 \circ R_2</m>, we would have these vertex
          transformations.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              1 \amp \mapsto 3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              2 \amp \mapsto 2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3 \amp \mapsto 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              4 \amp \mapsto 5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              5 \amp \mapsto 4
            </mrow>
          </md>
          This is the reflection <m>F_2</m>, so <m>F_3 \circ R_2</m>.
          Using similar vertex calcluation for all the entries, we
          produce the following multiplication table for <m>D_5</m>.
          <me>
            \begin{array}{c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c}
              \cdot \amp \Id \amp R_1 \amp R_2 \amp R_3 \amp R_4 \amp
                F_1 \amp F_2 \amp F_3 \amp F_4 \amp F_5 \\
              \Id \amp \Id \amp R_1 \amp R_2 \amp R_3 \amp R_4 \amp
                F_1 \amp F_2 \amp F_3 \amp F_4 \amp F_5 \\
              R_1 \amp R_1 \amp R_2 \amp R_3 \amp R_4 \amp \Id \amp
                F_4 \amp F_5 \amp F_1 \amp F_2 \amp F_3 \\
              R_2 \amp R_2 \amp R_3 \amp R_4 \amp \Id \amp R_1 \amp
                F_2 \amp F_3 \amp F_4 \amp F_1 \amp F_2 \\
              R_3 \amp R_3 \amp R_4 \amp \Id \amp R_1 \amp R_2 \amp
                F_5 \amp F_1 \amp F_2 \amp F_3 \amp F_4 \\
              R_4 \amp R_4 \amp \Id \amp R_1 \amp R_2 \amp R_3 \amp
                F_3 \amp F_4 \amp F_5 \amp F_1 \amp F_2 \\ 
              F_1 \amp F_1 \amp F_3 \amp F_5 \amp F_2 \amp F_4 \amp
                \Id \amp R_3 \amp R_1 \amp R_4 \amp R_2 \\
              F_2 \amp F_2 \amp F_4 \amp F_1 \amp F_3 \amp F_5 \amp
                R_2 \amp \Id \amp R_3 \amp R_1 \amp R_4 \\
              F_3 \amp F_3 \amp F_5 \amp F_2 \amp F_4 \amp F_1 \amp
                R_4 \amp R_2 \amp \Id \amp R_3 \amp R_1 \\
              F_4 \amp F_4 \amp F_1 \amp F_3 \amp F_5 \amp F_2 \amp
                R_1 \amp R_4 \amp R_2 \amp \Id \amp R_3 \\
              F_5 \amp F_5 \amp F_2 \amp F_4 \amp F_1 \amp F_3 \amp
                R_3 \amp R_1 \amp R_4 \amp R_2 \amp \Id \\
            \end{array}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="week6-proofs">
    <title>Proof Questions</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider two rotations in <m>\RR^2</m>, by angles
          <m>\theta</m> amd <m>\phi</m>. Use the general form of a
          matrix for a rotaion, prove that the composition of these
          two rotations is the rotation by the angle <m>(\theta +
          \phi)</m>. (You will need to use some trigonometric
          identities to prove this.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The general form of a rotation by <m>\theta</m> is 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \cos \theta \amp - \sin \theta \\
              \sin \theta \amp \cos \theta
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>.
          We can make the same matrix for the anlge <m>\phi</m>.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \cos \phi \amp - \sin \phi \\
              \sin \phi \amp \cos \phi
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>.
          We compose these two matrices. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                \cos \theta \amp - \sin \theta \\
                \sin \theta \amp \cos \theta
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                \cos \phi \amp - \sin \phi \\
                \sin \phi \amp \cos \phi
              \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                (\cos \theta) (\cos \phi) - (\sin \theta)(\sin \phi) \amp
                -(\cos \theta) (\sin \phi) - (\sin \theta)(\cos \phi) \\
                (\sin \theta) (\cos \phi) + (\cos \theta)(\sin \phi) \amp
                -(\sin \theta) (\sin \phi) + (\cos \theta)(\cos \phi) 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Now we need trig identities. Each of these four matrix
          entires is a sum identity. Replacing those according to
          identities drawn from some formula sheet or other reference,
          we get this matrix.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              \cos (\theta + \phi) \amp -\sin (\theta + \phi) \\
              \sin (\theta + \phi) \amp \cos (\theta + \phi)
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
          This is precisely the matrix form for rotation by the angle
          <m>(\theta + \phi)</m>. Therefore, we have prove that the
          matrix multiplication, and hence the composition, of two
          rotations produces the rotation by the sum of the two
          angles.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that any reflection in <m>\RR^2</m> composes with
          itself to produce the identity. (Use the general matrix for
          these reflections).
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The general form a reflection over the line spanned by the
          <emph>unit</emph> vector <m>\left( \begin{matrix} a \\ b
          \end{matrix} \right)</m> is 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix}
              a^2 - b^2 \amp 2ab \\ 
              2ab \amp b^2 - a^2 
            \end{matrix} \right)  
          </me>.
          Since we have a unit vector, we know <m>a^2 + b^2 =
          1</m>. This fact will be important to the proof. How we take
          this matrix and multiply it by itself to do the composition
          of the reflection with itself. We'll have to do some algebra
          with the resulting terms in the new matrix. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left( \begin{matrix}
                a^2 - b^2 \amp 2ab \\ 
                2ab \amp b^2 - a^2 
              \end{matrix} \right)  
              \left( \begin{matrix}
                a^2 - b^2 \amp 2ab \\ 
                2ab \amp b^2 - a^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                (a^2 - b^2)^2 + (2ab)(2ab) \amp
                (a^2-b^2)(2ab) + (2ab)(b^2-a^2) \\
                (2ab)(a^2-b^2) + (b^2-a^2)(2ab) \amp
                (2ab)(2ab) + (b^2-a^2)^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                a^4 - 2a^2b^2 + b^4 + 4a^2b^2 \amp
                (a^2-b^2)(2ab) - (a^2-b^2)(2ab) \\
                (2ab)(a^2-b^2) - (2ab)(a^2-b^2) \amp
                4a^2b^2 + b^2 - 2a^2b^2 + a^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                a^4 + 2a^2b^2 + b^4 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp b^2 + 2a^2b^2 + a^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                (a^2+b^2)^2 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp (a^2+b^2)^2 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \left( \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 0 \\
                0 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          In the last step, we use the important fact about the unit
          vector. We end up with the identity matrix, which is what we
          wanted, so the proof is finished. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
